data.content:
Yes! MSTest v3.4+ supports **typed tuples** with `DynamicData`, eliminating `object[]`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — compile-time type checking on your test data
- Array literals `["valid@email.com", true]` → tuple literals `("valid@email.com", true)`
- The `[DynamicData]` attribute stays the same

This gives you compiler errors if you accidentally put an `int` where a `string` is expected, instead of a runtime failure.
